WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.340 --> 00:00:09.577
♪

2
00:00:35.669 --> 00:00:38.037
And you stand there.
in my house...

3
00:00:38.038 --> 00:00:39.507
I'm sick and tired of...

4
00:00:40.108 --> 00:00:42.775
What an awful. awful thing.

5
00:00:42.776 --> 00:00:45.878
And when all is said and
done. you just made it worse.

6
00:00:45.879 --> 00:00:46.946
This is just the truth!

7
00:00:46.947 --> 00:00:48.781
It's high time you faced...

8
00:01:13.707 --> 00:01:15.175
<i>♪ We're up here</i>

9
00:01:15.176 --> 00:01:17.645
<i>♪ Under the sun. the
moon. and stars ♪</i>

10
00:01:18.546 --> 00:01:22.483
<i>♪ The galaxies above
are so far apart ♪</i>

11
00:01:23.317 --> 00:01:26.686
<i>♪ But I see you on
the block each day ♪</i>

12
00:01:26.687 --> 00:01:29.323
<i>♪ I wanted to reach out</i>

13
00:01:32.993 --> 00:01:34.194
- Hey.
- Hey.

14
00:01:34.195 --> 00:01:36.063
Nice one... big hands.

15
00:01:44.372 --> 00:01:45.506
Karl?

16
00:01:46.174 --> 00:01:47.408
And you're Cassandra.

17
00:01:47.908 --> 00:01:48.776
Hi.

18
00:01:48.777 --> 00:01:50.378
I'm not normally this late.

19
00:01:51.679 --> 00:01:53.946
No. I am. Um. but...

20
00:01:53.947 --> 00:01:55.616
It's okay. I'll get used to it.

21
00:01:56.049 --> 00:01:57.418
Um...

22
00:01:57.851 --> 00:02:01.222
Uh. I mean... assuming
we do this again.

23
00:02:03.123 --> 00:02:04.525
You don't look like your photo.

24
00:02:05.393 --> 00:02:06.526
Not in a bad way.

25
00:02:06.527 --> 00:02:08.295
Oh. Off to a roaring start.

26
00:02:08.296 --> 00:02:09.796
Don't let me interrupt.

27
00:02:09.797 --> 00:02:12.131
I'm just here to let you know
about our specials today.

28
00:02:12.132 --> 00:02:14.635
So... I'll get you started.

29
00:02:15.236 --> 00:02:16.404
We have a...

30
00:02:16.970 --> 00:02:18.406
oyster chowder.

31
00:02:18.972 --> 00:02:20.040
It's piping hot.

32
00:02:20.641 --> 00:02:24.911
And for dessert. a
passion fruit sorbet.

33
00:02:24.912 --> 00:02:26.145
Something to drink?

34
00:02:26.146 --> 00:02:27.480
This water is fine. thank you.

35
00:02:27.481 --> 00:02:29.249
Water. Exciting.

36
00:02:29.250 --> 00:02:30.650
Same here.

37
00:02:30.651 --> 00:02:31.985
Perfect.

38
00:02:35.756 --> 00:02:36.923
She's a friend of yours?

39
00:02:36.924 --> 00:02:38.625
She was until
about a minute ago.

40
00:02:38.626 --> 00:02:40.293
She owns the place. so...

41
00:02:40.294 --> 00:02:41.662
We ought to be nice.

42
00:02:42.563 --> 00:02:44.932
Karl. look. Before we
get any further. um...

43
00:02:46.099 --> 00:02:47.467
this probably won't work.

44
00:02:47.468 --> 00:02:49.269
I'm sure you're a
decent guy. but...

45
00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:51.604
bottom line. I don't know
that I want this with anyone.

46
00:02:51.605 --> 00:02:52.739
This?

47
00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:54.741
- A relationship.
- Oh. um...

48
00:02:54.742 --> 00:02:55.776
Yeah.

49
00:02:56.677 --> 00:02:57.745
How about lunch?

50
00:02:59.647 --> 00:03:00.947
We both want lunch. I hope.

51
00:03:00.948 --> 00:03:02.516
Yes. God. yes.

52
00:03:20.100 --> 00:03:21.601
This is Carlyle Burke.

53
00:03:21.602 --> 00:03:23.303
I can't take your
call right now

54
00:03:23.304 --> 00:03:25.305
but it's important to me.

55
00:03:25.306 --> 00:03:27.340
Leave a message.

56
00:03:27.341 --> 00:03:28.542
Carlyle?

57
00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:32.712
Forty-something.

58
00:03:32.713 --> 00:03:35.882
Newly single. older
doesn't always equal wiser.

59
00:03:35.883 --> 00:03:38.518
but I like to think
I'm making progress.

60
00:03:38.519 --> 00:03:39.353
Hmm.

61
00:03:39.354 --> 00:03:41.188
Your profile. I liked it.

62
00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:44.824
It did not say what
you do. though.

63
00:03:44.825 --> 00:03:46.827
I'm the Chief of Police.

64
00:03:51.232 --> 00:03:52.832
No. you're joking.

65
00:03:52.833 --> 00:03:53.867
No.

66
00:03:55.002 --> 00:03:57.036
Um. yeah. That's
why I kept it vague

67
00:03:57.037 --> 00:03:58.871
'cause you don't
exactly come right out.

68
00:03:58.872 --> 00:04:00.573
No. I. I get that.

69
00:04:00.574 --> 00:04:03.644
Lonely top cop. new in
town. Seeks soulmate.

70
00:04:04.812 --> 00:04:06.212
- Chief of Police.
- Mm-hmm.

71
00:04:06.213 --> 00:04:08.180
And no offense. you guys
have a difficult job.

72
00:04:08.181 --> 00:04:10.082
There's plenty of good
cops too. yada yada.

73
00:04:10.083 --> 00:04:12.753
But of all the types I ever
imagined myself with a...

74
00:04:13.754 --> 00:04:14.754
Your turn.

75
00:04:16.256 --> 00:04:18.325
Um... types?

76
00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:20.593
Point taken.

77
00:04:20.594 --> 00:04:21.662
Wow.

78
00:04:22.863 --> 00:04:25.398
Do you always do
that? The sphinx.

79
00:04:25.399 --> 00:04:27.234
That's an interesting question.

80
00:04:27.601 --> 00:04:28.736
Do you always do that?

81
00:04:29.870 --> 00:04:31.439
The self-sabotage.

82
00:04:33.073 --> 00:04:34.041
Oh. hell yeah.

83
00:04:34.042 --> 00:04:35.174
- Yeah?
- Mm-hmm.

84
00:04:36.243 --> 00:04:38.745
Um. well... It's charming.

85
00:04:40.414 --> 00:04:41.415
Cheers.

86
00:04:59.032 --> 00:04:59.967
Corporal Yen?

87
00:04:59.968 --> 00:05:01.200
Yes. That's me.

88
00:05:01.201 --> 00:05:02.935
Excellent. I'm Isabella.

89
00:05:02.936 --> 00:05:03.771
Nice to meet you.

90
00:05:03.772 --> 00:05:05.938
Come on. Through here.

91
00:05:05.939 --> 00:05:08.074
And this is where it
all happens. sort of.

92
00:05:08.075 --> 00:05:10.076
Sergeant Sokolowski.
this is Corporal Yen.

93
00:05:10.077 --> 00:05:11.644
You'll meet all these
other guys later.

94
00:05:11.645 --> 00:05:12.645
- Sergeant.
- Welcome.

95
00:05:12.646 --> 00:05:13.980
Heard a lot of
really good things.

96
00:05:13.981 --> 00:05:16.549
The detective who took
down a cartel in Philly.

97
00:05:16.550 --> 00:05:18.618
Yeah. Well. I was
part of the team.

98
00:05:18.619 --> 00:05:20.319
- Smart and humble.
- Mmhmm.

99
00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:21.455
I resent her already.

100
00:05:22.055 --> 00:05:24.090
Uh. is Chief Alberg...

101
00:05:24.091 --> 00:05:25.925
The boss is out to lunch.

102
00:05:25.926 --> 00:05:26.993
That's not a warning.

103
00:05:26.994 --> 00:05:28.561
In fact. he's
totally the opposite.

104
00:05:28.562 --> 00:05:30.663
He's literally having lunch.

105
00:05:30.664 --> 00:05:32.264
This is Officer Kendrick.

106
00:05:32.265 --> 00:05:33.265
From Philly?

107
00:05:33.266 --> 00:05:34.266
Sixers fan.

108
00:05:34.267 --> 00:05:35.635
Oh. all the way.

109
00:05:35.636 --> 00:05:36.636
Andy.

110
00:05:36.637 --> 00:05:37.637
Edwina.

111
00:05:37.638 --> 00:05:39.338
And this will be your desk.

112
00:05:39.339 --> 00:05:41.141
The lockers are through there.

113
00:05:42.009 --> 00:05:44.677
So... How do you
like Gibsons so far?

114
00:05:44.678 --> 00:05:46.145
First 10 minutes... not bad.

115
00:05:46.146 --> 00:05:48.415
It's small... and
sometimes weird.

116
00:05:48.416 --> 00:05:51.018
But give it a chance.
I bet you'll love it.

117
00:05:53.521 --> 00:05:54.654
Tell you the truth.

118
00:05:54.655 --> 00:05:56.490
I didn't know they
still had librarians.

119
00:05:57.257 --> 00:05:59.291
I mean. obviously
there's still books.

120
00:05:59.292 --> 00:06:03.095
and. uh. and. and I like
books. but. uh. somehow

121
00:06:03.096 --> 00:06:05.598
I just don't... I don't
think of libraries.

122
00:06:05.599 --> 00:06:08.368
What do you think about. Karl?

123
00:06:09.202 --> 00:06:10.336
You know. my daughters read.

124
00:06:10.337 --> 00:06:11.337
Okay.

125
00:06:11.338 --> 00:06:12.472
Yeah. Two of them.

126
00:06:12.473 --> 00:06:13.807
Well. more like
one and a half.

127
00:06:14.608 --> 00:06:16.543
Uh. Steph's the eldest.
She's off to university.

128
00:06:16.544 --> 00:06:18.177
She still talks to me. but...

129
00:06:18.178 --> 00:06:19.946
But Holly's 16. so...

130
00:06:19.947 --> 00:06:21.314
What'd you do to her?

131
00:06:22.149 --> 00:06:23.150
I failed. I guess.

132
00:06:24.618 --> 00:06:26.152
Uh. Holly's with her mom?

133
00:06:26.153 --> 00:06:27.153
Mm-hmm.

134
00:06:27.154 --> 00:06:28.522
Divided loyalties?

135
00:06:31.492 --> 00:06:33.159
I can say something
glib and stupid.

136
00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:34.061
Oh. that'd be good.

137
00:06:34.062 --> 00:06:35.362
Yeah.

138
00:06:38.131 --> 00:06:39.299
How about you?

139
00:06:40.033 --> 00:06:42.969
My loyalties? Uh...
few but fierce.

140
00:06:42.970 --> 00:06:44.737
You've never been married?

141
00:06:44.738 --> 00:06:46.206
I got close once.

142
00:06:47.575 --> 00:06:49.076
I mean close-ish.

143
00:06:50.210 --> 00:06:52.211
Here we go. Fish and chips.

144
00:06:52.212 --> 00:06:53.647
And a burger.

145
00:06:54.815 --> 00:06:56.583
- Thank you.
- Enjoy.

146
00:07:05.559 --> 00:07:08.561
I'd love to see you
again. If that'd be okay.

147
00:07:08.562 --> 00:07:09.929
Go ahead and call.

148
00:07:09.930 --> 00:07:11.031
Okay.

149
00:07:18.005 --> 00:07:19.206
Yeah?

150
00:07:21.341 --> 00:07:22.442
What?

151
00:07:22.743 --> 00:07:23.943
Did someone notice anything?

152
00:07:23.944 --> 00:07:25.612
A vehicle. sounds
from the house?

153
00:07:25.613 --> 00:07:26.913
You got it. Corporal.

154
00:07:26.914 --> 00:07:28.114
Corporal. good to see you.

155
00:07:28.115 --> 00:07:29.849
Sergeant Sokolowski's inside.

156
00:07:29.850 --> 00:07:30.917
Tell me everything.

157
00:07:30.918 --> 00:07:32.952
Uh. vic's name
was Carlyle Burke.

158
00:07:32.953 --> 00:07:34.086
Eighty-five years old.

159
00:07:34.087 --> 00:07:35.522
Guy who found him
isn't much younger.

160
00:07:35.523 --> 00:07:36.623
George Wilcox.

161
00:07:36.624 --> 00:07:38.190
Says he just dropped
by to say hello.

162
00:07:38.191 --> 00:07:39.727
Your first homicide. kid?

163
00:07:40.761 --> 00:07:42.394
You get used to it.

164
00:07:42.395 --> 00:07:44.064
Some first day. huh. Corporal?

165
00:07:44.765 --> 00:07:47.067
Single blow. looks
like. No forced entry.

166
00:07:52.039 --> 00:07:54.307
Doesn't look like
anything's missing. but...

167
00:08:02.616 --> 00:08:03.617
Chief?

168
00:08:08.622 --> 00:08:09.590
Tidy room.

169
00:08:09.591 --> 00:08:10.991
No obvious signs
of a struggle.

170
00:08:12.092 --> 00:08:13.293
Blood splatter minimal.

171
00:08:14.995 --> 00:08:16.096
Somebody's library books.

172
00:08:21.902 --> 00:08:23.436
Okay. Rest of the house.

173
00:08:27.908 --> 00:08:29.142
Hi.

174
00:08:30.343 --> 00:08:31.443
Yep.

175
00:08:31.444 --> 00:08:33.112
Hi. Hi.

176
00:08:33.113 --> 00:08:35.147
I think he's been saying Tom.

177
00:08:35.148 --> 00:08:36.148
Hi.

178
00:08:36.149 --> 00:08:37.618
It's probably his name.

179
00:08:38.151 --> 00:08:39.620
Hi.

180
00:08:40.788 --> 00:08:41.788
He must've bought it today

181
00:08:41.789 --> 00:08:43.656
or else someone
else gave it to him.

182
00:08:43.657 --> 00:08:44.991
Maybe Wilcox brought it?

183
00:08:44.992 --> 00:08:47.327
No. he says he's a
gardener. not a fisherman.

184
00:09:19.126 --> 00:09:20.393
Mr. Wilcox.

185
00:09:21.361 --> 00:09:22.662
I'm Chief Alberg.

186
00:09:22.663 --> 00:09:23.963
So you're the boss. are you?

187
00:09:23.964 --> 00:09:26.299
They said you wanted to
ask me some questions.

188
00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:27.868
You okay?

189
00:09:28.368 --> 00:09:30.402
There's gonna be one
hell of a hullabaloo

190
00:09:30.403 --> 00:09:32.571
once people figure
out what's happened.

191
00:09:32.572 --> 00:09:34.306
I'd like you to show
me how you found him.

192
00:09:34.307 --> 00:09:35.307
Can you do that?

193
00:09:35.308 --> 00:09:36.643
I'll do what I can.

194
00:09:36.644 --> 00:09:38.645
Was the door open
when you got here?

195
00:09:38.646 --> 00:09:40.312
No. I knocked a
couple of times.

196
00:09:40.313 --> 00:09:41.480
No answer.

197
00:09:41.481 --> 00:09:44.383
So I tried the doorknob.
It wasn't locked.

198
00:09:44.384 --> 00:09:46.719
I decided to go in
and see how he was.

199
00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:48.822
He is 85. you know.

200
00:09:49.657 --> 00:09:51.391
Was 85.

201
00:09:57.030 --> 00:09:58.666
Was Mr. Burke in ill health?

202
00:09:59.599 --> 00:10:00.867
How the hell should I know?

203
00:10:00.868 --> 00:10:03.003
Eighty-five years
old. At that age...

204
00:10:03.704 --> 00:10:06.506
The whole bag of bones
is wearing out fast.

205
00:10:07.074 --> 00:10:08.775
At any minute
something essential

206
00:10:08.776 --> 00:10:10.276
could just let go on you.

207
00:10:10.277 --> 00:10:13.213
Yeah. no. I know the
feeling myself some days.

208
00:10:14.414 --> 00:10:17.249
So you. um... you came inside.

209
00:10:17.250 --> 00:10:20.887
I. uh... I think I
shouted something.

210
00:10:20.888 --> 00:10:22.189
I dropped my books.

211
00:10:22.455 --> 00:10:24.590
I didn't... well...

212
00:10:24.591 --> 00:10:26.226
I wasn't thinking
all that clearly.

213
00:10:27.427 --> 00:10:28.861
And then?

214
00:10:28.862 --> 00:10:30.062
Called 911.

215
00:10:30.063 --> 00:10:31.098
Hmm.

216
00:10:33.633 --> 00:10:34.901
Was he a...

217
00:10:34.902 --> 00:10:37.137
was he a good friend
of yours. Mr. Wilcox?

218
00:10:38.105 --> 00:10:39.773
We. uh... knew each other.

219
00:10:41.208 --> 00:10:42.709
You came here
fairly often though?

220
00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:44.611
Not... not really. no.

221
00:10:46.146 --> 00:10:47.446
Well. look around.

222
00:10:47.447 --> 00:10:49.750
Tell me if you see
anything unusual.

223
00:10:52.652 --> 00:10:54.053
That.

224
00:10:54.054 --> 00:10:55.487
That's unusual.

225
00:10:55.488 --> 00:10:56.723
Anything else?

226
00:10:56.724 --> 00:10:57.758
Look...

227
00:10:58.926 --> 00:11:00.592
I don't know.

228
00:11:00.593 --> 00:11:02.595
It's. it's just. um...

229
00:11:04.397 --> 00:11:05.799
I'm sorry.

230
00:11:10.070 --> 00:11:11.237
I couldn't find anything.

231
00:11:11.238 --> 00:11:13.273
We'll need your
fingerprints for comparison.

232
00:11:13.974 --> 00:11:15.407
Now?

233
00:11:15.408 --> 00:11:17.109
Sid. let's get
Mr. Wilcox a ride.

234
00:11:17.110 --> 00:11:18.577
Yep.

235
00:11:18.578 --> 00:11:19.946
Expect a phone call.

236
00:11:19.947 --> 00:11:21.948
We'll have some more
questions about Mr. Burke.

237
00:11:21.949 --> 00:11:24.016
who his friends were.
that sort of thing.

238
00:11:24.017 --> 00:11:25.584
What about my library books?

239
00:11:25.585 --> 00:11:27.987
Oh. I'll have to keep
those. They're evidence.

240
00:11:27.988 --> 00:11:28.989
For what?

241
00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:31.758
One more question.

242
00:11:31.759 --> 00:11:34.260
Do you know anyone who might
have wanted Mr. Burke dead?

243
00:11:34.261 --> 00:11:35.494
No. I didn't.

244
00:11:35.495 --> 00:11:36.529
Hmm.

245
00:11:37.330 --> 00:11:39.999
I'd like to go home now.
if you wouldn't mind.

246
00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:41.033
Of course.

247
00:11:41.034 --> 00:11:42.335
This way. Mr. Wilcox.

248
00:11:48.776 --> 00:11:49.777
Hey. guys?

249
00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:51.644
Give us the room.

250
00:12:37.157 --> 00:12:38.425
What's missing?

251
00:12:40.093 --> 00:12:41.594
The balance is off.

252
00:12:44.097 --> 00:12:45.164
Balance.

253
00:12:45.165 --> 00:12:46.899
Imagine you're
looking at a painting.

254
00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:48.568
Both ends. there and there.

255
00:12:49.202 --> 00:12:50.403
What do you see?

256
00:12:52.605 --> 00:12:53.740
Nothing.

257
00:12:54.341 --> 00:12:55.674
Yeah. that's my point.

258
00:12:55.675 --> 00:12:58.611
Doesn't it look like
something should be there?

259
00:13:01.381 --> 00:13:03.182
Sure. Yeah. possibly.

260
00:13:03.183 --> 00:13:04.550
If you're like one
of those people

261
00:13:04.551 --> 00:13:06.219
who kinda wants
everything in order.

262
00:13:06.786 --> 00:13:08.421
Well. look at the room.

263
00:13:10.190 --> 00:13:11.790
If they were valuable.
we got a motive.

264
00:13:11.791 --> 00:13:12.926
Maybe.

265
00:13:14.127 --> 00:13:15.428
Let's find out about the fish.

266
00:13:16.363 --> 00:13:18.564
Oh. yeah... I'm
already on that.

267
00:13:18.565 --> 00:13:20.033
Find out who was
clearing deadfall.

268
00:13:21.902 --> 00:13:23.069
The fresh sawdust out back.

269
00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:24.571
You didn't notice?

270
00:13:25.605 --> 00:13:27.106
Eyes wide. Sid.

271
00:13:27.107 --> 00:13:29.109
There'll be no stopping you.

272
00:13:37.250 --> 00:13:38.251
Good.

273
00:14:06.346 --> 00:14:07.680
Other hand. please.

274
00:14:12.419 --> 00:14:13.585
Thank you.

275
00:14:17.357 --> 00:14:19.326
Oh... Only a few words.

276
00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:21.760
I'm sorry. that was
presumptuous of me.

277
00:14:21.761 --> 00:14:23.162
As far as I know.
both your parents

278
00:14:23.163 --> 00:14:24.864
were born and
raised in Portland.

279
00:14:25.865 --> 00:14:28.267
Philadelphia. actually.

280
00:14:28.268 --> 00:14:29.601
But my ye-ye's from Shanghai.

281
00:14:29.602 --> 00:14:31.637
Uh. Myra. That's...
that's my wife.

282
00:14:31.638 --> 00:14:34.506
We both love to travel.
Hong Kong twice.

283
00:14:34.507 --> 00:14:35.707
Uh. but never Shanghai.

284
00:14:35.708 --> 00:14:37.277
Maybe that's your next trip.

285
00:14:38.545 --> 00:14:40.013
You're old before you know.

286
00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:43.450
At some point the walls
start closing in on you.

287
00:14:44.484 --> 00:14:45.818
Then it's done.

288
00:14:46.786 --> 00:14:48.621
Finita la commedia.

289
00:15:37.904 --> 00:15:38.937
Steph.

290
00:15:38.938 --> 00:15:40.939
I know. I know. Text
don't call. but...

291
00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:42.009
I'm old.

292
00:15:43.176 --> 00:15:44.443
You speak to Holly?

293
00:15:44.444 --> 00:15:45.844
Well. texted.

294
00:15:45.845 --> 00:15:47.546
You know. like normal people.

295
00:15:47.547 --> 00:15:49.681
I don't think she
hates you or anything.

296
00:15:49.682 --> 00:15:51.350
It's the break. She
has a boyfriend.

297
00:15:51.351 --> 00:15:52.351
I think she changed her mind

298
00:15:52.352 --> 00:15:53.552
and was afraid
to tell you that.

299
00:15:53.553 --> 00:15:54.686
Afraid?

300
00:15:54.687 --> 00:15:57.123
Dad... you expect
a lot from yourself

301
00:15:57.124 --> 00:15:58.290
and from other people.

302
00:15:58.291 --> 00:15:59.858
Sometimes that's
hard to deal with.

303
00:15:59.859 --> 00:16:00.926
I... uh. no.

304
00:16:00.927 --> 00:16:02.394
That's... I... I don't expect.

305
00:16:02.395 --> 00:16:03.930
Yeah. but you do.

306
00:16:04.297 --> 00:16:06.198
I don't care. I'm
as bad as you are.

307
00:16:06.199 --> 00:16:07.967
But Holly's different.

308
00:16:08.768 --> 00:16:11.470
So... how is the
Sunshine Coast?

309
00:16:11.471 --> 00:16:12.704
As great as you remember?

310
00:16:12.705 --> 00:16:14.740
You know. it is
like I remember.

311
00:16:14.741 --> 00:16:16.276
Some of it. anyway.

312
00:16:17.210 --> 00:16:19.378
Sometimes I look
at a view and...

313
00:16:19.379 --> 00:16:21.547
I saw that when I was a kid.

314
00:16:21.548 --> 00:16:23.282
It's starting to
feel like home.

315
00:16:23.283 --> 00:16:25.551
Does this mean
you've met someone?

316
00:16:25.552 --> 00:16:27.887
No. Nothing like that.

317
00:16:30.123 --> 00:16:31.457
We had lunch.

318
00:16:31.458 --> 00:16:32.824
That's amazing.

319
00:16:32.825 --> 00:16:36.428
But the coast itself...
something about small towns.

320
00:16:36.429 --> 00:16:37.829
you get to be who you are.

321
00:16:37.830 --> 00:16:39.631
Hmm. Go outside the box.

322
00:16:39.632 --> 00:16:41.567
Follow your
tinfoil-hat hunches.

323
00:16:41.568 --> 00:16:44.303
Yeah. Go do my job.
Thank you very much.

324
00:16:44.304 --> 00:16:47.074
Investigate without six
layers of bureaucracy.

325
00:16:47.907 --> 00:16:49.408
I think I may get
myself a sailboat.

326
00:16:49.409 --> 00:16:50.277
Ooh.

327
00:16:50.278 --> 00:16:51.778
Very nice.

328
00:16:52.445 --> 00:16:55.414
So... what's her name?

329
00:16:55.415 --> 00:16:56.815
The one you haven't met?

330
00:16:56.816 --> 00:16:58.351
Cassandra.

331
00:17:03.423 --> 00:17:06.192
So. you saw George
Wilcox walk past?

332
00:17:06.193 --> 00:17:07.826
Yeah. about 2:30.

333
00:17:07.827 --> 00:17:09.929
I don't know if he
saw me on the deck.

334
00:17:10.463 --> 00:17:11.963
He's a good fella. George.

335
00:17:11.964 --> 00:17:14.666
And your grandson.
Riley. is it?

336
00:17:14.667 --> 00:17:16.034
Seems we missed him yesterday.

337
00:17:16.035 --> 00:17:18.437
Well he-he. he
keeps himself busy.

338
00:17:18.438 --> 00:17:20.038
helping people out.

339
00:17:20.039 --> 00:17:22.209
Uh. look... he
didn't see nothing!

340
00:17:26.946 --> 00:17:28.013
Riley Erlandson.

341
00:17:28.014 --> 00:17:30.382
Oh. come on. come
on. He's just a kid.

342
00:17:30.383 --> 00:17:31.550
Just... just...

343
00:17:31.551 --> 00:17:33.185
I'm Corporal Yen.

344
00:17:33.186 --> 00:17:34.186
Oh...

345
00:17:35.988 --> 00:17:37.289
Finley holds out

346
00:17:37.290 --> 00:17:40.459
her grandfather's old
hand-mad hunting map.

347
00:17:40.460 --> 00:17:42.529
as Tyler and Kaitlyn
gather round.

348
00:17:43.029 --> 00:17:44.996
The legend says
that the elder tree

349
00:17:44.997 --> 00:17:47.534
is more than 400 years old.

350
00:17:48.034 --> 00:17:49.836
But this tree is special...

351
00:17:50.403 --> 00:17:51.670
Cassandra.

352
00:17:51.671 --> 00:17:53.205
George! Hi.

353
00:17:53.206 --> 00:17:54.241
Hi.

354
00:17:55.708 --> 00:17:58.010
Ah! What? Oh my goodness.

355
00:17:58.711 --> 00:18:01.413
It is beautiful. Thank you.

356
00:18:01.414 --> 00:18:02.581
You're welcome.

357
00:18:02.582 --> 00:18:04.317
You know. I really
love saying your name.

358
00:18:05.051 --> 00:18:07.719
Cassandra Lee has such
a wonderful lilt to it.

359
00:18:09.722 --> 00:18:10.857
There.

360
00:18:11.858 --> 00:18:13.225
Met someone. have you?

361
00:18:13.226 --> 00:18:15.194
Well. had lunch with.

362
00:18:15.195 --> 00:18:16.195
Great.

363
00:18:16.663 --> 00:18:19.598
Don't get me wrong.
independence is a fine thing.

364
00:18:19.599 --> 00:18:21.568
Only highly overrated.

365
00:18:26.606 --> 00:18:28.374
You looking for
something in particular?

366
00:18:28.375 --> 00:18:29.676
A good mystery. maybe.

367
00:18:30.210 --> 00:18:31.911
A mystery? You?

368
00:18:32.845 --> 00:18:34.946
Well. yeah. It's
a great choice.

369
00:18:34.947 --> 00:18:36.882
Um... the Wednesday night
book club's discussing

370
00:18:36.883 --> 00:18:39.218
the modern crime novel
and Dostoevsky comes up

371
00:18:39.219 --> 00:18:40.419
again and again.

372
00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:41.421
Spoiler alert.

373
00:18:42.355 --> 00:18:44.022
Raskolnikov confesses.

374
00:18:44.023 --> 00:18:45.023
Hmm.

375
00:18:52.199 --> 00:18:53.700
I was the one who
found the body.

376
00:18:54.301 --> 00:18:55.635
Carlyle Burke.

377
00:18:55.935 --> 00:18:57.135
Oh my God.

378
00:18:57.136 --> 00:18:58.928
That's the reason I'm
here without my books.

379
00:18:59.439 --> 00:19:00.739
The cops kept them.

380
00:19:00.740 --> 00:19:03.108
Never mind the library
books. How are you doing?

381
00:19:03.109 --> 00:19:05.077
Well... I was
right next to him.

382
00:19:05.312 --> 00:19:06.478
It.

383
00:19:06.479 --> 00:19:07.479
The corpse.

384
00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:09.448
As close as I am to you now.

385
00:19:09.449 --> 00:19:10.549
George. that's awful.

386
00:19:10.550 --> 00:19:11.917
You know. you're
more than welcome

387
00:19:11.918 --> 00:19:13.119
to come over for a visit.

388
00:19:13.820 --> 00:19:15.120
Sometime. Anytime.

389
00:19:16.055 --> 00:19:16.956
It's been a while.

390
00:19:16.957 --> 00:19:18.324
- Yeah.
- We could have. uh...

391
00:19:18.325 --> 00:19:19.926
rosehip tea from
my greenhouse.

392
00:19:20.627 --> 00:19:21.660
Okay.

393
00:19:21.661 --> 00:19:22.661
Good.

394
00:19:27.434 --> 00:19:28.968
You weren't keen
to talk to us.

395
00:19:29.769 --> 00:19:31.337
You can understand
how that might look.

396
00:19:31.338 --> 00:19:33.473
Like I got nothing
to say to you.

397
00:19:34.607 --> 00:19:35.975
It might.

398
00:19:36.509 --> 00:19:37.609
On the other hand...

399
00:19:37.610 --> 00:19:39.011
The fish guy...

400
00:19:39.512 --> 00:19:43.082
Talk to him instead of
hassling innocent people.

401
00:19:43.316 --> 00:19:44.317
Fish guy.

402
00:19:45.252 --> 00:19:48.620
The cops were asking
who sells fish.

403
00:19:48.621 --> 00:19:51.923
There's a guy. crappy
old van with rainbows.

404
00:19:51.924 --> 00:19:53.492
Going door to door.

405
00:19:53.493 --> 00:19:54.526
That's good to know.

406
00:19:54.527 --> 00:19:56.462
He's a weird-looking dude.

407
00:19:56.463 --> 00:19:57.797
A black guy.

408
00:19:58.698 --> 00:20:01.000
Sorry. A person of color.

409
00:20:02.101 --> 00:20:03.436
Can I leave now?

410
00:20:04.103 --> 00:20:05.337
She's a good hire. boss.

411
00:20:05.338 --> 00:20:06.838
Yeah. she's smart.

412
00:20:06.839 --> 00:20:08.040
Asian.

413
00:20:09.642 --> 00:20:11.311
You're a good man. Sid.

414
00:20:11.778 --> 00:20:13.045
Keep evolving.

415
00:20:14.314 --> 00:20:16.316
That's what my daughter
keeps telling me.

416
00:20:16.849 --> 00:20:17.650
The brilliant one?

417
00:20:17.651 --> 00:20:18.885
Yeah. Steph.

418
00:20:19.852 --> 00:20:21.453
Mine keep telling
me to lose weight.

419
00:20:21.454 --> 00:20:23.154
All five of 'em.

420
00:20:23.155 --> 00:20:26.292
Maybe the... maybe the
other old guy saw him.

421
00:20:26.293 --> 00:20:27.293
George Wilcox. you mean?

422
00:20:27.294 --> 00:20:29.696
Yeah. he went by around 12:30.

423
00:20:31.798 --> 00:20:33.666
Your grandpa said 2:30.

424
00:20:34.834 --> 00:20:37.036
No. my grandpa was asleep.

425
00:20:40.407 --> 00:20:41.841
He's hiding something.

426
00:20:42.475 --> 00:20:44.075
He has a record.
breaking and entering.

427
00:20:44.076 --> 00:20:45.344
Where are we with
the fish guy?

428
00:20:45.345 --> 00:20:46.678
Oh. I'm looking
harder as of now.

429
00:20:46.679 --> 00:20:47.846
It's a robbery gone wrong.

430
00:20:47.847 --> 00:20:49.481
Okay. well. so
what was stolen?

431
00:20:49.482 --> 00:20:50.582
Guy gets spooked.

432
00:20:50.583 --> 00:20:52.083
Doesn't have time
to grab everything.

433
00:20:52.084 --> 00:20:54.252
Ask around the senior center.
see where that leads you.

434
00:20:54.253 --> 00:20:56.655
I wanna know if the victim
had friends. visitors.

435
00:20:56.656 --> 00:20:59.024
Maybe someone knows if he
had valuables in there.

436
00:20:59.025 --> 00:21:00.158
He probably had cleaners.

437
00:21:00.159 --> 00:21:01.393
Good one.

438
00:21:01.394 --> 00:21:02.594
Assuming it was a robbery.

439
00:21:02.595 --> 00:21:04.229
it'd be worth keeping
an eye on the place.

440
00:21:04.230 --> 00:21:06.565
There's a high-end
security monitoring system.

441
00:21:06.566 --> 00:21:08.066
Burke just didn't
have it activated.

442
00:21:08.067 --> 00:21:09.836
Well. let's activate it.

443
00:21:10.337 --> 00:21:13.038
I wanna know if anyone else
saw George Wilcox at 12:30.

444
00:21:22.048 --> 00:21:24.516
Contact info. Carlyle
Burke's sister.

445
00:21:24.517 --> 00:21:25.617
Thanks Isabella.

446
00:21:25.618 --> 00:21:27.253
I'm. uh. really sorry
about your loss.

447
00:21:27.787 --> 00:21:30.122
My brother was 85 years old.

448
00:21:30.557 --> 00:21:32.090
We don't live forever.

449
00:21:32.091 --> 00:21:35.026
Well. the circumstances though.
that must be disturbing to you.

450
00:21:35.027 --> 00:21:36.762
Homicide. so I understand?

451
00:21:36.763 --> 00:21:37.864
Mm-hmm.

452
00:21:38.631 --> 00:21:40.899
Um... when will you be
coming out. Ms. Ridings?

453
00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:42.368
To Gibsons.

454
00:21:42.369 --> 00:21:43.802
Oh. I don't think
I'll be coming out.

455
00:21:43.803 --> 00:21:45.571
You're a long
way from Chicago.

456
00:21:45.572 --> 00:21:47.906
Well. the funeral. settling
your brother's affairs.

457
00:21:47.907 --> 00:21:49.441
You're his next of kin.

458
00:21:49.442 --> 00:21:50.442
Oh.

459
00:21:51.043 --> 00:21:52.978
I take it the two of
you were estranged.

460
00:21:52.979 --> 00:21:56.114
Estrangement implies
a previous affection.

461
00:21:56.115 --> 00:21:58.417
He didn't like me.
I didn't like him.

462
00:21:58.418 --> 00:21:59.785
Who was close to your brother?

463
00:21:59.786 --> 00:22:01.454
Who else have you talked to?

464
00:22:01.921 --> 00:22:03.656
A man named George Wilcox.

465
00:22:05.958 --> 00:22:07.927
I remember George Wilcox.

466
00:22:09.228 --> 00:22:12.064
Yeah. A great. tall fella.

467
00:22:13.132 --> 00:22:15.300
He was Carlyle's best man.

468
00:22:15.301 --> 00:22:17.135
At your brother's
wedding. you mean?

469
00:22:17.136 --> 00:22:18.770
Oh God. what a wedding.

470
00:22:18.771 --> 00:22:23.676
And that long best man
with his even longer face.

471
00:22:24.811 --> 00:22:26.112
Seething.

472
00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:35.787
Afternoon. Mr. Wilcox.

473
00:22:35.788 --> 00:22:37.456
Don't you ever wear a uniform?

474
00:22:37.457 --> 00:22:39.791
No uniforms. no police car.

475
00:22:39.792 --> 00:22:41.661
How am I supposed to
take you seriously?

476
00:22:43.630 --> 00:22:44.597
This help?

477
00:22:44.598 --> 00:22:46.364
Nuh-uh. Got a gun?

478
00:22:46.365 --> 00:22:48.200
Why. do you think
I'll need one?

479
00:22:52.605 --> 00:22:53.706
Your wife?

480
00:22:54.941 --> 00:22:57.877
Myra. She died last March.

481
00:22:59.011 --> 00:23:00.547
You still miss her.

482
00:23:01.948 --> 00:23:03.482
Now that right there

483
00:23:03.483 --> 00:23:05.984
is what's wrong
with all you cops.

484
00:23:05.985 --> 00:23:07.454
In a nutshell.

485
00:23:08.054 --> 00:23:09.522
You still miss her.

486
00:23:09.989 --> 00:23:11.558
Jesus wept.

487
00:23:14.193 --> 00:23:16.563
Audrey. your sister.

488
00:23:22.401 --> 00:23:24.136
So... any suspects?

489
00:23:25.638 --> 00:23:26.872
Not really.

490
00:23:26.873 --> 00:23:29.340
An unknown person went
into Mr. Burke's house

491
00:23:29.341 --> 00:23:31.477
armed with a blunt instrument.

492
00:23:31.478 --> 00:23:33.512
Why the hell would
Carlyle have let him in?

493
00:23:33.513 --> 00:23:35.414
That's an interesting question.

494
00:23:35.748 --> 00:23:39.018
Maybe the killer used something
that he found inside the house.

495
00:23:39.586 --> 00:23:42.521
It's probably out in the
middle of the ocean by now.

496
00:23:42.522 --> 00:23:44.823
You can be a very
irritating man. Mr. Wilcox.

497
00:23:44.824 --> 00:23:46.392
Anybody ever tell you that?

498
00:23:46.859 --> 00:23:49.995
I don't suppose you dropped
in on Carlyle twice yesterday.

499
00:23:49.996 --> 00:23:51.598
And why would I do that?

500
00:23:52.999 --> 00:23:55.067
You're here for a
reason. I presume?

501
00:23:55.668 --> 00:23:57.369
Your. uh. fingerprints.

502
00:23:58.104 --> 00:23:59.671
Were all over the living room.

503
00:23:59.672 --> 00:24:01.407
I was somewhat. um...

504
00:24:02.509 --> 00:24:05.778
how shall I say...
discombobulated.

505
00:24:06.579 --> 00:24:07.580
Right.

506
00:24:09.682 --> 00:24:11.049
Let's not waste any more time

507
00:24:11.050 --> 00:24:14.185
with this cantankerous
old man act.

508
00:24:14.186 --> 00:24:17.123
I know Carlyle Burke was
your brother-in-Law. so...

509
00:24:18.858 --> 00:24:20.192
Start talking.

510
00:24:24.564 --> 00:24:25.865
We met years ago.

511
00:24:26.365 --> 00:24:29.301
We both taught at
uni on the mainland.

512
00:24:30.036 --> 00:24:32.704
I taught Russian history.
Carlyle taught music.

513
00:24:32.705 --> 00:24:33.772
Yeah.

514
00:24:33.773 --> 00:24:35.240
I never trusted him.

515
00:24:35.241 --> 00:24:38.578
Every year. Myra and I. we'd
have this Christmas party.

516
00:24:39.579 --> 00:24:41.713
And that's where
he met her. Audrey.

517
00:24:41.714 --> 00:24:43.783
Did you tell Audrey
you didn't trust him?

518
00:24:47.720 --> 00:24:49.154
Myra and I had to
leave for Germany

519
00:24:49.155 --> 00:24:50.455
right after the wedding.

520
00:24:50.456 --> 00:24:52.592
I had a job there teaching.

521
00:24:53.593 --> 00:24:54.793
Two year exchange.

522
00:24:54.794 --> 00:24:55.762
And that was...

523
00:24:55.763 --> 00:24:56.996
'76. '77.

524
00:24:57.564 --> 00:24:59.464
That's when Audrey was killed.

525
00:24:59.465 --> 00:25:00.767
Car accident.

526
00:25:01.801 --> 00:25:03.001
After the funeral.

527
00:25:03.002 --> 00:25:05.504
I didn't see him again
for 35. 40 years.

528
00:25:06.172 --> 00:25:07.574
Not until he showed up here.

529
00:25:08.174 --> 00:25:09.909
You say you never
trusted him...

530
00:25:11.310 --> 00:25:13.312
but you never really
got to know him.

531
00:25:14.847 --> 00:25:15.847
So...

532
00:25:16.282 --> 00:25:18.183
maybe you were all
wrong about Carlyle.

533
00:25:18.184 --> 00:25:20.019
You may be right about that.

534
00:25:22.021 --> 00:25:22.989
Yeah.

535
00:25:22.990 --> 00:25:24.490
That could be true.

536
00:25:27.927 --> 00:25:32.131
Something Burke's sister
said at the wedding.

537
00:25:32.965 --> 00:25:34.601
Long sad faces.

538
00:25:35.134 --> 00:25:36.134
Seething.

539
00:25:36.135 --> 00:25:38.436
That was. what...
50 years ago.

540
00:25:38.437 --> 00:25:40.438
Whoever smashed
Carlyle Burke's skull.

541
00:25:40.439 --> 00:25:43.008
that was a crime of passion.

542
00:25:43.009 --> 00:25:44.711
I've been back for
five years now.

543
00:25:45.044 --> 00:25:48.714
My mom likes my brother
better. to be honest.

544
00:25:48.715 --> 00:25:52.518
Um. but he has a partner
and three kids. so...

545
00:25:53.152 --> 00:25:54.552
Is that why you
came back here...

546
00:25:54.553 --> 00:25:55.621
to look after her?

547
00:25:55.622 --> 00:25:56.988
No. God. no.

548
00:25:56.989 --> 00:25:59.625
But... to be closer.

549
00:25:59.626 --> 00:26:02.294
And I love the coast.
I grew up here.

550
00:26:03.963 --> 00:26:05.030
And?

551
00:26:05.031 --> 00:26:06.665
What is this. an
interrogation?

552
00:26:06.666 --> 00:26:08.233
Oh. I thought we
were divulging.

553
00:26:08.234 --> 00:26:09.301
Well. divulge.

554
00:26:10.302 --> 00:26:12.503
- Big city police work.
- Mmhmm.

555
00:26:12.504 --> 00:26:16.508
It was taking its toll
on my marriage. 20 years.

556
00:26:17.309 --> 00:26:19.145
I'm not sure I
ever saw it coming.

557
00:26:20.512 --> 00:26:22.915
I looked up and then it
had all fallen apart.

558
00:26:23.916 --> 00:26:26.152
It was my fault. I
stopped noticing.

559
00:26:27.219 --> 00:26:28.921
I've always been good at that.

560
00:26:31.924 --> 00:26:33.225
How was that?

561
00:26:33.993 --> 00:26:35.093
So what were you looking for

562
00:26:35.094 --> 00:26:37.528
when you signed on
to a dating site?

563
00:26:37.529 --> 00:26:38.430
You.

564
00:26:40.099 --> 00:26:41.867
Um... it's my daughter's idea.

565
00:26:41.868 --> 00:26:42.835
Ah.

566
00:26:42.836 --> 00:26:44.169
The one who still talks to me.

567
00:26:44.170 --> 00:26:46.071
So. basically I'm
a shot in the dark.

568
00:26:46.072 --> 00:26:47.238
How about you?

569
00:26:47.239 --> 00:26:49.776
I wasn't meeting
anyone. And. um...

570
00:26:50.777 --> 00:26:53.579
Men... seem to find
me disconcerting.

571
00:26:54.413 --> 00:26:56.414
Please disconcert me.

572
00:26:56.415 --> 00:26:59.550
Well. I signed on with the
hope of finding a pleasant.

573
00:26:59.551 --> 00:27:02.187
not unattractive.
courteous male person

574
00:27:02.188 --> 00:27:04.555
with whom I can have
adequate conversation

575
00:27:04.556 --> 00:27:06.258
and spectacular sex.

576
00:27:08.394 --> 00:27:09.627
How's the conversation?

577
00:27:09.628 --> 00:27:11.430
So far it's not bad.

578
00:27:11.864 --> 00:27:13.966
I have a friend who
lives up the road.

579
00:27:23.409 --> 00:27:24.410
Audrey?

580
00:27:27.379 --> 00:27:29.047
No. it's me.

581
00:27:29.048 --> 00:27:30.648
George. are you all right?

582
00:27:30.649 --> 00:27:32.451
Yeah. sure. Fine.

583
00:27:33.219 --> 00:27:34.720
The sun was in my eyes.

584
00:27:34.721 --> 00:27:35.922
Hope you don't mind.

585
00:27:36.622 --> 00:27:37.957
Is he the one?

586
00:27:39.291 --> 00:27:40.292
Is now a bad time?

587
00:27:41.627 --> 00:27:44.162
No. no. no. It's all good.

588
00:27:44.163 --> 00:27:45.231
All good.

589
00:27:46.132 --> 00:27:48.633
I should've called before
showing up. I'm sorry.

590
00:27:48.634 --> 00:27:51.070
Since when did you become
friends with the police force?

591
00:27:51.904 --> 00:27:54.173
Not the entire
force. just Karl.

592
00:27:56.342 --> 00:27:58.343
I see you've been digging
out there. Mr. Wilcox.

593
00:27:58.344 --> 00:28:00.747
Even at this time of
year. It's impressive.

594
00:28:02.348 --> 00:28:04.282
I'm thinking about
planting a garden myself.

595
00:28:04.283 --> 00:28:05.650
Are you now?

596
00:28:05.651 --> 00:28:07.685
You should see George's
garden in June.

597
00:28:07.686 --> 00:28:08.820
It is spectacular.

598
00:28:08.821 --> 00:28:11.622
The hydrangeas are
blue and then purple.

599
00:28:11.623 --> 00:28:13.459
My mother used to
grow geraniums.

600
00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:15.762
Sunflowers and hollyhocks.

601
00:28:16.763 --> 00:28:18.797
There's an amazing
sense of grace

602
00:28:18.798 --> 00:28:20.299
to be found with gardening.

603
00:28:21.667 --> 00:28:24.270
That is. as long as you can
handle the responsibility.

604
00:28:25.004 --> 00:28:28.039
It's hard to tell if
your interest is genuine.

605
00:28:28.040 --> 00:28:29.308
Mr. Alberg.

606
00:28:29.608 --> 00:28:32.044
Hard to know if you're
that sort of man.

607
00:28:37.850 --> 00:28:39.018
Never mind those.

608
00:28:39.685 --> 00:28:41.153
It's my pleasure.

609
00:28:47.726 --> 00:28:48.726
You changed something.

610
00:28:49.195 --> 00:28:50.195
Nope.

611
00:28:51.530 --> 00:28:52.730
Something's different.

612
00:28:52.731 --> 00:28:54.533
I ought to know. I'm
the one who lives here.

613
00:28:56.568 --> 00:28:57.735
Karl.

614
00:28:57.736 --> 00:28:59.171
Goodnight. Mr. Alberg.

615
00:29:06.678 --> 00:29:08.146
Uh. well that was nice.

616
00:29:08.147 --> 00:29:11.416
Uh. it's been a while since
I've had an evening out.

617
00:29:11.417 --> 00:29:12.884
That was an evening out?

618
00:29:12.885 --> 00:29:14.419
You must not get out much.

619
00:29:16.388 --> 00:29:17.823
Go for a night cap somewhere?

620
00:29:17.824 --> 00:29:20.258
♪ If you say it's
okay. it's okay ♪

621
00:29:20.259 --> 00:29:21.326
It is late.

622
00:29:21.327 --> 00:29:22.327
Okay.

623
00:29:25.364 --> 00:29:27.699
♪ If you say it's
okay with you ♪

624
00:29:30.602 --> 00:29:31.871
Call me.

625
00:29:34.706 --> 00:29:37.775
♪ Be there to hold you tight.

626
00:29:37.776 --> 00:29:39.344
♪ hold you tight

627
00:29:39.345 --> 00:29:42.013
♪ Love you all
through the night ♪

628
00:29:42.014 --> 00:29:45.784
♪ If it's okay with you

629
00:29:47.086 --> 00:29:50.857
♪ If it's okay with you

630
00:30:32.498 --> 00:30:34.332
I drink single malt.

631
00:30:34.333 --> 00:30:36.135
You've come to
the right place.

632
00:30:40.806 --> 00:30:42.607
I haven't... I haven't
finished unpacking.

633
00:30:42.608 --> 00:30:44.275
Yeah. how long
have you been here?

634
00:30:44.276 --> 00:30:45.945
Uh... three. four months.

635
00:30:47.846 --> 00:30:49.247
I'm busy with work.

636
00:30:49.248 --> 00:30:50.282
Uh-huh.

637
00:30:52.151 --> 00:30:53.484
That's my mom.

638
00:30:53.485 --> 00:30:55.786
I mean. not her
obviously. but her work.

639
00:30:55.787 --> 00:30:57.256
Shirley Alberg.

640
00:30:57.589 --> 00:31:00.927
She was just starting to
get noticed when she passed.

641
00:31:01.793 --> 00:31:03.128
You checked me out.

642
00:31:03.129 --> 00:31:05.664
Librarians call it research.

643
00:31:07.333 --> 00:31:08.434
I'm sorry about your mom.

644
00:31:10.302 --> 00:31:11.703
I was 16. so...

645
00:31:12.271 --> 00:31:14.306
Yeah. I'm pretty much over it.

646
00:31:17.643 --> 00:31:18.978
Where is that?

647
00:31:19.711 --> 00:31:21.980
That is Half Moon Bay.

648
00:31:21.981 --> 00:31:23.148
What?

649
00:31:23.149 --> 00:31:24.182
Mm-hmm.

650
00:31:24.183 --> 00:31:26.952
My-my mom stayed
here a few times.

651
00:31:26.953 --> 00:31:27.953
Ah.

652
00:31:28.220 --> 00:31:31.557
I came here with her
once. um. years ago.

653
00:31:32.191 --> 00:31:33.358
I was nine.

654
00:31:33.359 --> 00:31:35.060
And-and you. what. you
camped on the beach

655
00:31:35.061 --> 00:31:36.161
while your mom painted?

656
00:31:36.162 --> 00:31:37.129
Kind of. yeah.

657
00:31:37.130 --> 00:31:38.396
Oh. you are such a Bohemian.

658
00:31:38.397 --> 00:31:39.464
Mm-hmm.

659
00:31:39.465 --> 00:31:41.466
And now you're the
Chief of Police.

660
00:31:41.467 --> 00:31:44.036
Surprises the heck out
of me too sometimes.

661
00:31:44.503 --> 00:31:45.503
Hm.

662
00:31:48.707 --> 00:31:50.075
What about your dad?

663
00:31:50.076 --> 00:31:51.676
Did he ever come
with you guys?

664
00:31:51.677 --> 00:31:53.579
Oh no. no. I mean. uh...

665
00:31:55.014 --> 00:31:56.714
I never had one.

666
00:31:56.715 --> 00:31:58.016
Yeah.

667
00:31:58.017 --> 00:32:00.152
Just me and my mom. far
back as I can recall.

668
00:32:02.354 --> 00:32:04.056
My mom really loved it here.

669
00:32:05.724 --> 00:32:07.693
Something she said
about the place.

670
00:32:08.527 --> 00:32:09.527
It. uh...

671
00:32:10.362 --> 00:32:11.863
it has a special
kind of peace.

672
00:32:12.731 --> 00:32:13.732
It heals.

673
00:32:14.700 --> 00:32:16.168
Sometimes you need
that. you know?

674
00:32:17.169 --> 00:32:18.169
Yeah. I do.

675
00:32:19.105 --> 00:32:21.207
Yeah. Maybe that's
why I'm back.

676
00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:23.542
Trying to reconnect
or something.

677
00:32:26.712 --> 00:32:28.213
Karl. do you have a cat?

678
00:32:28.214 --> 00:32:30.349
Possibly. Yeah.

679
00:32:31.017 --> 00:32:32.017
Felix.

680
00:32:32.718 --> 00:32:35.121
That's. uh. that's
what I call him anyway.

681
00:32:36.422 --> 00:32:38.257
He sort of disappeared.

682
00:32:39.425 --> 00:32:40.692
But. uh...

683
00:32:41.960 --> 00:32:43.562
Now the food's
getting eaten. so...

684
00:32:45.364 --> 00:32:47.565
You said you had single malt.

685
00:32:47.566 --> 00:32:48.566
Yeah.

686
00:32:49.301 --> 00:32:51.270
Guys say all kinds of stuff.

687
00:32:56.708 --> 00:32:58.610
♪

688
00:33:00.646 --> 00:33:01.646
♪ Don't...

689
00:33:03.582 --> 00:33:05.417
♪ Take the night

690
00:33:08.154 --> 00:33:09.821
♪ Don't leave here

691
00:33:11.657 --> 00:33:13.158
♪ Just make it right

692
00:33:13.159 --> 00:33:14.159
God...

693
00:33:14.760 --> 00:33:16.161
The last time I had
a proper date...

694
00:33:16.162 --> 00:33:17.829
it's been a minute.

695
00:33:18.464 --> 00:33:20.666
We'll take it as
slowly as you want.

696
00:33:22.234 --> 00:33:23.901
What are the other options?

697
00:33:23.902 --> 00:33:26.572
♪ Do you expect me to live

698
00:33:27.573 --> 00:33:29.675
♪ That kind of life?

699
00:33:30.342 --> 00:33:32.143
♪ I won't

700
00:33:32.144 --> 00:33:33.679
♪ I'll fight

701
00:33:36.615 --> 00:33:42.088
♪ Don't take the night

702
00:33:43.955 --> 00:33:50.629
♪ Take the gun and
I'll take the knife ♪

703
00:33:52.664 --> 00:33:58.170
♪ Don't take the night

704
00:34:00.839 --> 00:34:05.710
♪ Don't take the night

705
00:34:05.711 --> 00:34:09.014
♪

706
00:35:58.790 --> 00:36:01.426
You crafty old bastard.

707
00:36:06.565 --> 00:36:07.899
Evening. George.

708
00:36:08.634 --> 00:36:10.402
What are you doing
out there. George?

709
00:36:11.437 --> 00:36:13.771
Rowed quite the
distance. didn't you?

710
00:36:13.772 --> 00:36:15.105
Had to get out past the shelf.

711
00:36:15.106 --> 00:36:16.674
I don't know what
you're talking about.

712
00:36:16.675 --> 00:36:17.775
The murder weapon. George.

713
00:36:17.776 --> 00:36:19.345
The one you buried
and then dug up.

714
00:36:19.911 --> 00:36:21.246
You chuck them both
or just the one

715
00:36:21.247 --> 00:36:22.681
you bashed his head in with?

716
00:36:23.415 --> 00:36:25.149
Doesn't matter 'cause
I'm gonna find them.

717
00:36:25.150 --> 00:36:27.952
Good! You look for whatever
you damn well please.

718
00:36:27.953 --> 00:36:29.086
I'm going to bed.

719
00:36:29.087 --> 00:36:30.455
Oh. you're a
determined man. George.

720
00:36:30.456 --> 00:36:31.923
Well. so am I.

721
00:36:33.191 --> 00:36:34.959
I'll have the sea
search people with me.

722
00:36:34.960 --> 00:36:37.194
Underwater drones. side scan
sonar. state of the art.

723
00:36:37.195 --> 00:36:39.030
There's nothing those
guys can't find.

724
00:36:39.498 --> 00:36:40.866
You don't frighten me.

725
00:36:42.100 --> 00:36:43.200
I just thought there might be

726
00:36:43.201 --> 00:36:44.635
something you'd
like to tell me.

727
00:36:44.636 --> 00:36:46.372
Well. you thought
wrong. sonny.

728
00:36:47.473 --> 00:36:48.806
I don't have
anything to tell you.

729
00:36:48.807 --> 00:36:50.375
You understand?

730
00:36:50.376 --> 00:36:51.677
Nothing.

731
00:37:08.694 --> 00:37:10.028
Karl?

732
00:37:15.401 --> 00:37:16.735
Karl?

733
00:37:17.736 --> 00:37:19.471
♪ Seems like sorrow

734
00:37:20.138 --> 00:37:21.473
Great.

735
00:37:22.708 --> 00:37:25.142
♪ Never done leave
nobody alone ♪

736
00:37:30.882 --> 00:37:34.820
♪ Maybe by tomorrow

737
00:37:35.821 --> 00:37:40.692
♪ We could lose the
thought of owning ♪

738
00:37:43.662 --> 00:37:47.098
♪

739
00:37:48.667 --> 00:37:51.737
♪ Baby. by tomorrow

740
00:37:52.170 --> 00:37:53.771
Good morning. boss.
You wanted to see us?

741
00:37:53.772 --> 00:37:55.540
It's uh. it's the old guy.

742
00:37:55.541 --> 00:37:56.907
George Wilcox?

743
00:37:56.908 --> 00:37:58.243
He's dumped the murder weapon.

744
00:37:59.578 --> 00:38:02.380
There's a shelf.
100 yards off shore.

745
00:38:02.381 --> 00:38:05.182
All the way across
that stretch of coast.

746
00:38:05.183 --> 00:38:07.552
Burke's place is
here. Wilcox is here.

747
00:38:07.553 --> 00:38:10.789
If he's smart. the old
bastard rowed out past it.

748
00:38:11.189 --> 00:38:13.223
And the old bastard's smart.

749
00:38:13.224 --> 00:38:15.626
Last night? I mean. why?

750
00:38:15.627 --> 00:38:17.127
Something to do
with the sister.

751
00:38:17.128 --> 00:38:18.763
Yeah. but we still...

752
00:38:18.764 --> 00:38:20.731
Of course we'll need a motive.

753
00:38:20.732 --> 00:38:22.132
But he did it. Sid.

754
00:38:22.133 --> 00:38:24.202
I was pretty convinced
yesterday. now I know.

755
00:38:24.903 --> 00:38:26.103
I'll get someone
to look through

756
00:38:26.104 --> 00:38:27.638
the security footage
from the house.

757
00:38:27.639 --> 00:38:28.706
Okay.

758
00:38:28.707 --> 00:38:29.974
And I need to know
if anybody else

759
00:38:29.975 --> 00:38:32.810
saw George Wilcox go
past that house at 12:30.

760
00:38:32.811 --> 00:38:35.145
We need to nail down
what's actually missing.

761
00:38:35.146 --> 00:38:36.213
Cleaning lady.

762
00:38:36.214 --> 00:38:37.748
Yeah. Found her. Do
you want me to...

763
00:38:37.749 --> 00:38:38.950
Now. Please.

764
00:38:39.250 --> 00:38:40.486
And find the fish guy.

765
00:38:40.952 --> 00:38:42.252
Anything else for me?

766
00:38:42.253 --> 00:38:43.588
Uh...

767
00:38:43.589 --> 00:38:45.457
some deodorant would be nice.

768
00:38:47.125 --> 00:38:48.659
For me. Sid.

769
00:38:48.660 --> 00:38:50.629
You smell as fresh as
a mountain morning.

770
00:39:22.994 --> 00:39:24.162
Karl Alberg.

771
00:39:24.930 --> 00:39:26.465
Look at you.

772
00:39:33.772 --> 00:39:35.040
Hi.

773
00:39:37.643 --> 00:39:38.677
Help you?

774
00:39:39.277 --> 00:39:40.979
It's a real old
timer. this guy.

775
00:39:42.013 --> 00:39:43.047
He won't eat.

776
00:39:43.048 --> 00:39:44.715
Tried bird seed.
whole grain bread.

777
00:39:44.716 --> 00:39:46.851
Nuh-uh. No. you need
to give him some mango.

778
00:39:46.852 --> 00:39:48.319
Maybe a slice of peach.

779
00:39:48.820 --> 00:39:49.688
Seriously?

780
00:39:49.689 --> 00:39:50.889
Yeah.

781
00:39:51.623 --> 00:39:53.692
So. I hear you folks
have been looking for me.

782
00:39:55.026 --> 00:39:56.227
Derek Farley.

783
00:39:58.630 --> 00:40:00.130
Yeah. I sold a
trout up the road.

784
00:40:00.131 --> 00:40:01.466
I just...

785
00:40:01.467 --> 00:40:03.133
I swear to God.
man. I don't know...

786
00:40:03.134 --> 00:40:05.135
Just tell me what
time you got there.

787
00:40:05.136 --> 00:40:06.370
What you saw.

788
00:40:06.371 --> 00:40:08.072
9:30. maybe 10:00 AM.

789
00:40:08.073 --> 00:40:10.040
But I rang that bell
and he opened the door.

790
00:40:10.041 --> 00:40:11.577
Did you see anyone with him?

791
00:40:12.478 --> 00:40:13.544
Anyone coming or going?

792
00:40:13.545 --> 00:40:14.713
No one.

793
00:40:15.346 --> 00:40:16.715
Did he say anything?

794
00:40:17.549 --> 00:40:19.416
Thanks for the fish.
something like that.

795
00:40:19.417 --> 00:40:21.752
Uh. no... wait. Um...

796
00:40:21.753 --> 00:40:25.356
No. he said he'd invited
a friend to lunch.

797
00:40:26.825 --> 00:40:27.993
Did he mention a name?

798
00:40:28.894 --> 00:40:30.496
Just an old friend.

799
00:40:31.229 --> 00:40:32.697
Invited him to lunch.

800
00:40:32.698 --> 00:40:34.032
Mm-hmm.

801
00:40:36.001 --> 00:40:37.935
Thanks Mr. Farley.
you've been helpful.

802
00:40:37.936 --> 00:40:39.705
- Really?
- Yeah. very.

803
00:40:40.238 --> 00:40:41.540
Semper Fi.

804
00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:43.241
Desert Storm.

805
00:40:44.175 --> 00:40:45.943
I moved here 20 years ago.

806
00:40:45.944 --> 00:40:48.379
Met my wife.
Better way to live.

807
00:40:51.016 --> 00:40:52.617
Mrs. Harris. we
appreciate your help.

808
00:40:52.618 --> 00:40:54.685
A tragedy. what a tragedy.

809
00:40:54.686 --> 00:40:55.686
Poor Mr. Burke.

810
00:40:55.687 --> 00:40:56.854
Yeah.

811
00:40:56.855 --> 00:40:58.422
I cleaned his house
for years. you know.

812
00:40:58.423 --> 00:41:01.693
like clockwork. every
second Saturday afternoon.

813
00:41:02.427 --> 00:41:04.061
What we need to do
is compile a list.

814
00:41:04.062 --> 00:41:06.230
anything of value that may
have been in the house.

815
00:41:06.231 --> 00:41:07.966
Because robbery
was the motive?

816
00:41:08.466 --> 00:41:10.468
Let's say we're doing
our due diligence.

817
00:41:11.102 --> 00:41:12.770
Well. he had a fair bit.

818
00:41:12.771 --> 00:41:15.906
Silverware and china.
Some old antiques.

819
00:41:15.907 --> 00:41:17.407
Of course people
love to say antique

820
00:41:17.408 --> 00:41:19.276
when they really mean old.

821
00:41:19.277 --> 00:41:20.646
Mrs. Harris...

822
00:41:21.312 --> 00:41:23.549
Have you ever
seen one of these?

823
00:41:24.282 --> 00:41:25.883
Trench art? Sure.

824
00:41:25.884 --> 00:41:28.385
Artwork made from
artillery shells.

825
00:41:28.386 --> 00:41:31.656
This is really good. Bit
of an artist yourself.

826
00:41:31.657 --> 00:41:33.558
Think carefully now. did
Carlyle Burke have...

827
00:41:33.559 --> 00:41:36.427
Two of 'em. There and there.

828
00:41:37.829 --> 00:41:38.963
You sure?

829
00:41:38.964 --> 00:41:40.931
Ever since I've been
cleaning his house.

830
00:41:40.932 --> 00:41:42.499
But they're not really
valuable though.

831
00:41:42.500 --> 00:41:43.601
you buy 'em online.

832
00:41:43.602 --> 00:41:45.970
Oh. yeah. Thank
you. Mrs. Harris.

833
00:41:45.971 --> 00:41:47.573
Thank you.

834
00:41:49.507 --> 00:41:50.507
Oh. uh. careful.

835
00:41:51.009 --> 00:41:52.777
Oh! Scene of the crime.

836
00:41:52.778 --> 00:41:54.012
Yes.

837
00:41:55.246 --> 00:41:57.816
It's probably out in the
middle of the ocean by now.

838
00:42:03.321 --> 00:42:04.322
So...

839
00:42:05.456 --> 00:42:07.357
We went for a walk.
visited a friend.

840
00:42:07.358 --> 00:42:08.860
and then walked some more.

841
00:42:09.527 --> 00:42:11.362
Okay. Promising start.

842
00:42:12.530 --> 00:42:16.501
He dropped me off at my
car and then I. um...

843
00:42:17.335 --> 00:42:18.869
I followed him
back to his place.

844
00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:20.537
Shut up!

845
00:42:20.538 --> 00:42:22.807
He's an artist. Who
would've thought?

846
00:42:22.808 --> 00:42:24.009
Okay. never mind that.

847
00:42:24.542 --> 00:42:25.877
He's actually very good.

848
00:42:27.112 --> 00:42:28.312
Artistically.

849
00:42:28.313 --> 00:42:29.947
And no. before you ask.

850
00:42:29.948 --> 00:42:32.017
he did not ask to
paint my portrait.

851
00:42:32.718 --> 00:42:33.818
I'm late for work.

852
00:42:33.819 --> 00:42:36.186
Okay. Cass. Cass...
This is great.

853
00:42:36.187 --> 00:42:37.221
It is.

854
00:42:37.222 --> 00:42:38.724
Whether you wanna
admit it or not.

855
00:42:39.157 --> 00:42:40.324
Be happy.

856
00:42:41.727 --> 00:42:43.194
Thank you.

857
00:42:44.630 --> 00:42:48.165
So. um... is it
just his hands?

858
00:42:48.166 --> 00:42:49.801
Okay. bye Phyll.

859
00:42:58.209 --> 00:42:59.210
Boss.

860
00:42:59.811 --> 00:43:01.812
That old accident
report from Bellingham.

861
00:43:01.813 --> 00:43:03.648
Burke's wife. Single vehicle.

862
00:43:03.649 --> 00:43:06.050
Turns out. driving too fast.
just went off the road.

863
00:43:06.051 --> 00:43:07.685
Second page is the
autopsy report.

864
00:43:07.686 --> 00:43:09.153
They gave her the works.

865
00:43:09.154 --> 00:43:11.822
Apparently George Wilcox
insisted death due to injury

866
00:43:11.823 --> 00:43:13.224
sustained in the crash.

867
00:43:13.859 --> 00:43:16.995
Also. there may have been some
old fractures that hadn't set.

868
00:43:17.495 --> 00:43:20.031
And possibly some
new ones. but...

869
00:43:20.565 --> 00:43:22.734
the rest of her was
too busted up to know.

870
00:43:25.603 --> 00:43:27.338
Anything from the
sea search guys?

871
00:43:30.175 --> 00:43:31.441
Big ocean.

872
00:43:31.442 --> 00:43:33.277
Yeah. well... I don't care
if they find anything.

873
00:43:33.278 --> 00:43:35.579
he can see them from his
window every time he looks out.

874
00:43:35.580 --> 00:43:39.250
Okay. Just hear me out.
Just. uh. devil's advocate.

875
00:43:39.851 --> 00:43:41.919
Let's say the old guy did
just go out for a row.

876
00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:43.788
I had an uncle.
slipped a gear...

877
00:43:43.789 --> 00:43:45.222
stopped wearing pants.

878
00:43:45.223 --> 00:43:46.456
Yeah.

879
00:43:46.457 --> 00:43:48.258
everyone confesses. Sid...

880
00:43:48.259 --> 00:43:50.061
sooner or later to somebody.

881
00:43:56.201 --> 00:43:58.135
George... Does something hurt?

882
00:43:58.136 --> 00:43:59.536
Does your heart hurt?

883
00:43:59.537 --> 00:44:00.570
No. it isn't that.

884
00:44:00.571 --> 00:44:02.106
I am going to take
you to a doctor.

885
00:44:02.107 --> 00:44:03.107
No!

886
00:44:03.709 --> 00:44:05.609
No. no. No doctors. Nuh-uh.

887
00:44:05.610 --> 00:44:07.544
Okay. Okay. No doctors.

888
00:44:07.545 --> 00:44:10.081
Come on. let me take you home.

889
00:44:18.256 --> 00:44:19.590
You gonna be okay?

890
00:44:20.625 --> 00:44:21.727
Fine.

891
00:44:24.562 --> 00:44:25.731
Thank you.

892
00:44:26.431 --> 00:44:27.665
For everything.

893
00:44:35.073 --> 00:44:36.441
What are they doing?

894
00:44:37.308 --> 00:44:38.643
Their job.

895
00:44:41.346 --> 00:44:43.480
I'm going away. Cassandra.

896
00:44:43.481 --> 00:44:44.648
Soon.

897
00:44:44.649 --> 00:44:46.183
Going away. Why?

898
00:44:46.184 --> 00:44:48.019
To be with my daughter.

899
00:44:48.987 --> 00:44:50.321
But your garden?

900
00:44:51.757 --> 00:44:53.491
I. uh... I don't
deserve it anymore.

901
00:44:54.592 --> 00:44:55.993
I-I just can't
stomach the thought

902
00:44:55.994 --> 00:44:58.295
of dying where Carlyle died.

903
00:44:58.296 --> 00:44:59.865
Being buried
where he's buried.

904
00:45:01.132 --> 00:45:02.667
But Myra's buried here too.

905
00:45:04.102 --> 00:45:05.102
Hmm.

906
00:45:06.004 --> 00:45:07.438
He's dead now.

907
00:45:08.106 --> 00:45:09.775
Why do you still
hate him so much?

908
00:45:14.813 --> 00:45:17.115
I've done a terrible
thing. Cassandra.

909
00:45:17.816 --> 00:45:18.816
And. uh...

910
00:45:19.717 --> 00:45:21.152
I need to atone.

911
00:45:22.353 --> 00:45:24.021
At first I wanted
to give myself up.

912
00:45:24.022 --> 00:45:25.991
but then I thought... prison?

913
00:45:26.524 --> 00:45:27.524
No.

914
00:45:27.525 --> 00:45:29.194
I. I... I can't.

915
00:45:30.728 --> 00:45:35.700
I can't spend the last days
of my life... behind bars.

916
00:45:37.836 --> 00:45:39.237
Not for him.

917
00:45:42.240 --> 00:45:43.508
George. What. uh...

918
00:45:44.976 --> 00:45:46.544
what am I supposed
to do with this?

919
00:45:48.980 --> 00:45:52.083
Do... whatever you need to do.

920
00:45:57.823 --> 00:45:58.856
Oh hey. Cassandra...

921
00:45:58.857 --> 00:46:00.225
Give me a minute.

922
00:46:10.768 --> 00:46:12.536
Sure... we could keep going.

923
00:46:12.537 --> 00:46:15.405
But it's more than 100.000
square yards of ocean.

924
00:46:15.406 --> 00:46:17.607
Rocks all over the bottom.
some as big as a truck.

925
00:46:17.608 --> 00:46:18.843
Keep going.

926
00:46:18.844 --> 00:46:19.844
Until?

927
00:46:19.845 --> 00:46:21.212
I tell you to stop.

928
00:46:32.423 --> 00:46:34.959
Well. well. The amazing
disappearing detective.

929
00:46:34.960 --> 00:46:37.427
I've heard about guys sneaking
out in the middle of the night.

930
00:46:37.428 --> 00:46:39.129
but from your own house?

931
00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:42.200
I was gonna suggest dinner. but
today's getting away from me.

932
00:46:42.934 --> 00:46:44.970
Maybe on the weekend
or something?

933
00:46:47.605 --> 00:46:48.874
Cassandra?

934
00:46:50.775 --> 00:46:53.278
I'd like to see you today. It
doesn't have to be for long.

935
00:46:54.812 --> 00:46:56.047
What's up?

936
00:46:59.417 --> 00:47:00.886
I saw police boats
on the water.

937
00:47:01.586 --> 00:47:03.753
Took a notion there might
be a weapon out there.

938
00:47:03.754 --> 00:47:04.789
And was there?

939
00:47:05.991 --> 00:47:07.725
There he is... sphinx.

940
00:47:08.894 --> 00:47:11.295
It was quite the
experience this morning.

941
00:47:11.296 --> 00:47:14.798
Waking up alone in your house
with bits of you lying around.

942
00:47:14.799 --> 00:47:16.133
hanging on the walls.

943
00:47:16.134 --> 00:47:17.601
I know. I'll. uh...

944
00:47:17.602 --> 00:47:19.937
I'll get the unpacking finished.

945
00:47:19.938 --> 00:47:22.607
You're an artist too.
Not just your mom.

946
00:47:23.308 --> 00:47:24.642
I went into the room.

947
00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:26.978
Those paintings.
they're. uh...

948
00:47:28.079 --> 00:47:29.447
they're amazing.

949
00:47:29.981 --> 00:47:31.415
And personal.

950
00:47:31.416 --> 00:47:33.284
So is was waking up
in someone else's bed.

951
00:47:34.452 --> 00:47:36.988
Not what I would've
expected from you. but...

952
00:47:37.788 --> 00:47:39.490
you take it seriously.
you're good.

953
00:47:42.193 --> 00:47:44.129
How's your friend.
George Wilcox?

954
00:47:45.931 --> 00:47:47.165
My God.

955
00:47:47.966 --> 00:47:49.499
Are those a policeman's eyes?

956
00:47:49.500 --> 00:47:51.335
They're my eyes.
I'm a policeman.

957
00:47:51.336 --> 00:47:52.337
Why...

958
00:47:53.171 --> 00:47:55.372
are you a policeman?

959
00:47:55.373 --> 00:47:57.342
Because I'm good at the job.

960
00:47:57.842 --> 00:47:59.110
I can imagine.

961
00:48:00.278 --> 00:48:01.478
And I like it.

962
00:48:01.479 --> 00:48:02.981
That's not an answer though.

963
00:48:03.648 --> 00:48:05.116
Why do you like it?

964
00:48:05.850 --> 00:48:08.486
I like figuring things
out. Solving things.

965
00:48:09.620 --> 00:48:11.656
I like serving and protecting.

966
00:48:13.058 --> 00:48:14.491
I know. a walking cliché.

967
00:48:14.492 --> 00:48:17.195
I thought so too until
my daughters were born.

968
00:48:19.197 --> 00:48:20.464
And what about justice?

969
00:48:20.465 --> 00:48:22.833
Oh. justice isn't
up to me. thank God.

970
00:48:23.634 --> 00:48:25.036
Thank God?

971
00:48:25.870 --> 00:48:27.472
The law lets you
know where you stand.

972
00:48:31.342 --> 00:48:32.343
I don't...

973
00:48:33.979 --> 00:48:37.047
think that George is doing
very well. to be honest.

974
00:48:37.048 --> 00:48:38.883
He. uh. came by
the library today.

975
00:48:39.517 --> 00:48:41.086
What he have to
say for himself?

976
00:48:43.388 --> 00:48:44.389
We just talked.

977
00:48:51.696 --> 00:48:53.763
You said you wanted
to... to meet.

978
00:48:53.764 --> 00:48:55.066
Well. what's up?

979
00:48:57.735 --> 00:48:59.570
I had a really nice
time last night.

980
00:49:00.738 --> 00:49:01.739
Me too.

981
00:49:08.746 --> 00:49:10.048
I should get back to work.

982
00:49:20.858 --> 00:49:22.627
Yeah. Sid. I'm on my way.

983
00:49:32.103 --> 00:49:34.404
Already did the living room.
kitchen and bathroom. Chief.

984
00:49:34.405 --> 00:49:35.940
Also the tool shed. No joy.

985
00:49:41.779 --> 00:49:42.880
Guy stuff.

986
00:49:43.714 --> 00:49:44.715
Yes. sir.

987
00:49:45.483 --> 00:49:46.951
Tools. Junk.

988
00:49:49.054 --> 00:49:50.388
What's outta place?

989
00:49:52.757 --> 00:49:54.958
Thing is. Chief. if we...

990
00:49:54.959 --> 00:49:57.261
had a better sense of
what we were looking for.

991
00:49:57.262 --> 00:49:58.595
that might help.

992
00:49:58.596 --> 00:50:00.830
Well. something that
should be there but isn't.

993
00:50:00.831 --> 00:50:03.101
Something that shouldn't
be here but is.

994
00:50:04.069 --> 00:50:06.002
Right. Right.

995
00:50:06.003 --> 00:50:08.005
Big picture first.
then details.

996
00:50:08.506 --> 00:50:09.774
Mm-hmm.

997
00:50:29.960 --> 00:50:31.362
That...

998
00:51:01.559 --> 00:51:02.960
Puzzle box.

999
00:51:03.694 --> 00:51:05.396
My ye-ye loved those.

1000
00:51:11.802 --> 00:51:14.904
"I can't live in fear.
Carlyle. I won't. Never again.

1001
00:51:14.905 --> 00:51:16.740
"May 15th. 1978.

1002
00:51:16.741 --> 00:51:18.242
"If you raise a
hand to me again...

1003
00:51:18.243 --> 00:51:19.743
George Wilcox.

1004
00:51:19.744 --> 00:51:21.010
You've always suspected.

1005
00:51:21.011 --> 00:51:22.646
You wait 40 years and
then you kill him?

1006
00:51:22.647 --> 00:51:23.647
- He did it. Sid.
- Okay.

1007
00:51:23.648 --> 00:51:24.748
But without a confession.

1008
00:51:24.749 --> 00:51:26.291
what are the odds
we're gonna get him?

1009
00:51:27.017 --> 00:51:28.853
Then I'll get a confession.

1010
00:51:45.670 --> 00:51:48.104
I'd like you to come
with me. Mr. Wilcox.

1011
00:51:48.105 --> 00:51:50.175
Oh... going downtown. are we?

1012
00:51:55.380 --> 00:51:57.248
I thought maybe you'd
come to say goodbye.

1013
00:51:58.082 --> 00:51:59.717
One of us going somewhere?

1014
00:52:00.518 --> 00:52:01.852
She didn't tell you?

1015
00:52:03.087 --> 00:52:05.189
I'm going to Montréal.

1016
00:52:05.190 --> 00:52:06.257
Um...

1017
00:52:06.757 --> 00:52:08.124
I can't let you do that.

1018
00:52:08.125 --> 00:52:09.593
Why not?

1019
00:52:09.594 --> 00:52:12.929
You've got nothing on me.
It's all circumstantial.

1020
00:52:12.930 --> 00:52:14.732
I'm not even a suspect.

1021
00:52:15.366 --> 00:52:18.469
I'm a person of interest.
And as free as a bird.

1022
00:52:19.304 --> 00:52:22.440
Speaking of birds. Carlyle
left you his parrot.

1023
00:52:35.986 --> 00:52:38.922
Sometimes it's harder than
you'd believe to kill someone.

1024
00:52:38.923 --> 00:52:41.058
You bash away and they
just refuse to die.

1025
00:52:42.092 --> 00:52:44.161
You speaking from
personal experience?

1026
00:52:45.596 --> 00:52:47.798
Sometimes it's just
one little smack.

1027
00:52:53.170 --> 00:52:54.772
He invited you for lunch.

1028
00:52:57.007 --> 00:52:58.575
Now why would he
have done that?

1029
00:52:58.576 --> 00:52:59.777
You tell me.

1030
00:53:01.512 --> 00:53:04.148
Maybe 'cause it was the
anniversary of Audrey's death?

1031
00:53:05.983 --> 00:53:08.285
Maybe Carlyle figured
time was short.

1032
00:53:08.286 --> 00:53:09.486
Eighty-five years old.

1033
00:53:09.487 --> 00:53:12.189
Like you said. George.
wearing out fast.

1034
00:53:12.790 --> 00:53:14.324
There were things
he wanted to say.

1035
00:53:14.325 --> 00:53:15.926
problem is he said them.

1036
00:53:16.461 --> 00:53:18.195
How am I doing so far. George?

1037
00:53:19.530 --> 00:53:22.667
See. I... I don't think you
came here planning to kill him.

1038
00:53:23.268 --> 00:53:25.001
But the man just
wouldn't shut up.

1039
00:53:25.002 --> 00:53:26.470
Would he. George?

1040
00:53:26.471 --> 00:53:28.205
He started talking
about your sister.

1041
00:53:28.973 --> 00:53:30.440
I'm warning you.

1042
00:53:30.441 --> 00:53:32.876
Audrey was broken
long before I met her.

1043
00:53:32.877 --> 00:53:36.980
And that is the truth and it's
time you faced up to that.

1044
00:53:36.981 --> 00:53:38.047
For your own sake.

1045
00:53:38.048 --> 00:53:39.215
Shut up!

1046
00:53:39.216 --> 00:53:40.650
Saying things you
couldn't stand to hear.

1047
00:53:40.651 --> 00:53:41.951
So you grabbed something.

1048
00:53:41.952 --> 00:53:43.453
Poor Audrey would've
been better off

1049
00:53:43.454 --> 00:53:44.788
if she'd never had a brother.

1050
00:53:44.789 --> 00:53:46.390
You just wanted
to make him stop.

1051
00:53:46.391 --> 00:53:48.292
She'd be better off
if you'd never...

1052
00:53:51.796 --> 00:53:53.464
And all of a sudden
there he is...

1053
00:53:54.532 --> 00:53:55.533
lying dead.

1054
00:53:56.634 --> 00:53:57.868
With his eyes open.

1055
00:53:59.870 --> 00:54:00.871
I know...

1056
00:54:01.839 --> 00:54:03.374
because I found the body.

1057
00:54:04.575 --> 00:54:05.876
Talk to me. George.

1058
00:54:07.011 --> 00:54:08.545
You don't need to carry this.

1059
00:54:10.715 --> 00:54:12.550
You miserable cops.

1060
00:54:13.884 --> 00:54:16.654
You have no idea
what I carry around.

1061
00:54:18.255 --> 00:54:19.256
I remember...

1062
00:54:20.190 --> 00:54:21.926
coming in the back door.

1063
00:54:23.861 --> 00:54:25.662
I could see him in
the living room.

1064
00:54:25.663 --> 00:54:27.064
Sitting in the chair?

1065
00:54:27.598 --> 00:54:28.999
Standing.

1066
00:54:29.734 --> 00:54:31.836
Beating her with
a razor strop.

1067
00:54:33.571 --> 00:54:35.005
Carlyle Burke?

1068
00:54:36.240 --> 00:54:37.542
My stepdad.

1069
00:54:39.109 --> 00:54:41.379
It started when
we were 14. 15.

1070
00:54:42.112 --> 00:54:44.949
He'd beat my twin sister every
time he went on a bender.

1071
00:54:46.083 --> 00:54:48.786
I'd hit him with anything
I could get my hands on.

1072
00:54:50.054 --> 00:54:53.624
He'd just pick me up and
throw me across the room.

1073
00:54:55.693 --> 00:54:57.193
You've probably heard
all this before.

1074
00:54:57.194 --> 00:54:58.863
haven't you. Mr. Alberg?

1075
00:54:59.464 --> 00:55:01.265
A man with your experience.

1076
00:55:02.367 --> 00:55:03.768
One day on the way home...

1077
00:55:04.402 --> 00:55:05.435
I heard Audrey's screams

1078
00:55:05.436 --> 00:55:07.237
all the way to the
top of the road.

1079
00:55:09.774 --> 00:55:12.810
I... wanted to kill him.

1080
00:55:16.547 --> 00:55:18.147
I ran down to where
his truck was parked

1081
00:55:18.148 --> 00:55:20.284
to grab the shotgun
off his rack.

1082
00:55:20.951 --> 00:55:22.453
I fired a shot in the air.

1083
00:55:23.220 --> 00:55:26.557
Get the hell out of here.
you miserable son of a bitch.

1084
00:55:29.460 --> 00:55:30.894
He. uh...

1085
00:55:30.895 --> 00:55:32.663
he was too far away
to grab the gun...

1086
00:55:33.297 --> 00:55:35.432
and too drunk to
think straight.

1087
00:55:35.433 --> 00:55:37.134
So he turned tail and...

1088
00:55:38.002 --> 00:55:40.104
stumbled back
towards his truck.

1089
00:55:40.671 --> 00:55:43.841
My mother ran after him.
yelling at him not to drive.

1090
00:55:45.075 --> 00:55:46.644
That she was sorry...

1091
00:55:48.312 --> 00:55:50.114
and begging him to
take her with him.

1092
00:55:52.016 --> 00:55:55.920
He fishtailed across the
yard. clipping the gate.

1093
00:55:56.687 --> 00:55:58.423
As he turned onto
the upper road...

1094
00:55:59.790 --> 00:56:02.427
I said to no one
in particular...

1095
00:56:04.194 --> 00:56:05.963
If there is a God in heaven...

1096
00:56:08.799 --> 00:56:12.136
I hope he drives the two of
them off the bloody cliff.

1097
00:56:18.042 --> 00:56:21.846
Sometime that evening...
two cops showed up.

1098
00:56:23.548 --> 00:56:24.982
They told us...

1099
00:56:25.950 --> 00:56:29.052
our father's truck had
been forced off the road

1100
00:56:29.053 --> 00:56:30.721
by a tractor trailer.

1101
00:56:32.457 --> 00:56:34.459
It had flipped over
the guardrail...

1102
00:56:35.693 --> 00:56:37.495
and plunged into the ocean.

1103
00:56:40.397 --> 00:56:41.732
So...

1104
00:56:44.001 --> 00:56:45.402
there is a God.

1105
00:56:52.510 --> 00:56:55.144
I failed my
sister. Mr. Alberg.

1106
00:56:55.145 --> 00:56:57.815
And I might just as well
have killed both my parents.

1107
00:57:00.851 --> 00:57:02.186
That's it.

1108
00:57:03.320 --> 00:57:05.255
I have nothing
more to say to you.

1109
00:57:26.877 --> 00:57:27.877
Is she here?

1110
00:57:27.878 --> 00:57:28.879
Uh. that way.

1111
00:57:37.087 --> 00:57:38.422
Your friend says he's leaving.

1112
00:57:39.557 --> 00:57:41.358
He's surprised you
didn't tell me.

1113
00:57:43.694 --> 00:57:45.194
I assume that we're
talking about...

1114
00:57:45.195 --> 00:57:46.731
You have something to tell me?

1115
00:57:48.265 --> 00:57:49.599
He did it.

1116
00:57:49.600 --> 00:57:50.800
He did it and you know that.

1117
00:57:50.801 --> 00:57:51.968
I'm not sure.

1118
00:57:51.969 --> 00:57:53.737
Do you have any idea
how serious this is?

1119
00:57:53.738 --> 00:57:56.072
Pretend I don't. Karl.
Pretend I'm an idiot.

1120
00:57:56.073 --> 00:57:57.473
If you're withholding
information...

1121
00:57:57.474 --> 00:57:59.242
Is that what I am
to you. a source?

1122
00:57:59.243 --> 00:58:00.744
Oh. Cassandra...

1123
00:58:00.745 --> 00:58:02.779
How many possible sources do
you screw in the course of...

1124
00:58:02.780 --> 00:58:03.614
A man is dead!

1125
00:58:03.615 --> 00:58:04.649
Do not...

1126
00:58:06.884 --> 00:58:08.384
Don't...

1127
00:58:08.385 --> 00:58:09.787
shout at me.

1128
00:58:13.958 --> 00:58:15.459
Karl. Listen...

1129
00:58:16.927 --> 00:58:19.829
If George Wilcox had told me
that he committed a crime...

1130
00:58:19.830 --> 00:58:22.498
I'd have looked in the legal
section and I'd have found

1131
00:58:22.499 --> 00:58:26.502
that a confession like that
isn't admissible evidence.

1132
00:58:26.503 --> 00:58:27.904
Even if he said the words.

1133
00:58:27.905 --> 00:58:29.840
Yeah. well. you might
wanna look again.

1134
00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:31.809
It is hearsay.

1135
00:58:32.910 --> 00:58:34.645
It wouldn't have
mattered what I said.

1136
00:58:36.747 --> 00:58:38.448
It might have mattered to me.

1137
00:58:39.917 --> 00:58:42.085
Karl. he is an old man.

1138
00:58:42.086 --> 00:58:44.320
He is giving up
everything he loves.

1139
00:58:44.321 --> 00:58:46.090
He's no danger to anyone.

1140
00:58:48.859 --> 00:58:50.994
Is it really so cut
and dry for you?

1141
00:58:50.995 --> 00:58:52.697
Is it really so damned clear?

1142
00:58:53.764 --> 00:58:54.764
No.

1143
00:58:55.299 --> 00:58:57.466
But I don't make the rules
and I don't get to break them.

1144
00:58:57.467 --> 00:59:00.036
Well. I wonder how you
carry it. Detective.

1145
00:59:00.037 --> 00:59:02.172
The weight of your
own integrity.

1146
00:59:04.308 --> 00:59:06.176
Hmm. Yeah.

1147
00:59:19.289 --> 00:59:22.358
Attention all passengers kindly
return to your vehicle...

1148
00:59:22.359 --> 00:59:24.695
the ferry is about to unload.

1149
00:59:35.405 --> 00:59:38.041
I have enough to
press charges. George.

1150
00:59:38.042 --> 00:59:42.713
Put it all together. there's
motive. opportunity. means.

1151
00:59:51.355 --> 00:59:53.023
You take care. now.

1152
00:59:56.526 --> 00:59:59.563
♪

1153
01:00:02.366 --> 01:00:05.770
♪

1154
01:00:07.004 --> 01:00:09.774
♪

1155
01:00:10.207 --> 01:00:13.277
♪ Everything will be okay ♪

1156
01:00:15.880 --> 01:00:18.582
♪ Everything will be fine

1157
01:00:19.283 --> 01:00:21.885
♪

1158
01:00:21.886 --> 01:00:24.922
♪ Everything will be okay

1159
01:00:27.291 --> 01:00:30.527
♪ Everything will be fine

1160
01:00:32.863 --> 01:00:34.030
♪ Everything will be...

1161
01:00:34.031 --> 01:00:35.598
Dear Mr. Alberg...

1162
01:00:35.599 --> 01:00:37.033
I understand you
asked my doctor

1163
01:00:37.034 --> 01:00:38.768
about the state of my health.

1164
01:00:38.769 --> 01:00:41.270
which he refused to divulge.

1165
01:00:41.271 --> 01:00:43.307
It would've been simpler
to have asked me.

1166
01:00:44.041 --> 01:00:47.745
Yes. I am dying. If
that's of any consequence.

1167
01:00:48.913 --> 01:00:52.783
I can't say I'm surprised
and definitely not dismayed.

1168
01:00:53.951 --> 01:00:56.653
I never liked this life
all that much anyway.

1169
01:00:57.788 --> 01:01:00.423
First of all. I'm
writing to say thank you.

1170
01:01:00.424 --> 01:01:03.093
It was kind of you to
let me see those letters.

1171
01:01:03.761 --> 01:01:06.230
It must have been a
frustrating time for you.

1172
01:01:06.931 --> 01:01:09.065
I know how much you cops
like to get your man

1173
01:01:09.066 --> 01:01:10.467
and all that crap.

1174
01:01:11.268 --> 01:01:13.302
Just think how much
harder it might have been

1175
01:01:13.303 --> 01:01:15.305
if I'd planned
the whole thing.

1176
01:01:15.806 --> 01:01:17.908
Still. you did get
your man in the end.

1177
01:01:18.943 --> 01:01:21.946
Yes. Mr. Alberg. I
killed Carlyle Burke.

1178
01:01:22.980 --> 01:01:26.583
There's my confession.
signed by my dying hand.

1179
01:01:27.651 --> 01:01:29.586
You can go ahead and
close your case now.

1180
01:01:30.354 --> 01:01:32.322
Finita la commedia.

1181
01:01:33.257 --> 01:01:36.861
P.S. I like you. Mr. Alberg.
in spite of everything.

1182
01:01:37.427 --> 01:01:40.496
And I know Cassandra cares
for you a great deal.

1183
01:01:40.497 --> 01:01:43.300
I'd be heartbroken if I
thought I'd spoiled that.

1184
01:01:45.169 --> 01:01:46.635
I received a letter.

1185
01:01:46.636 --> 01:01:47.972
Hmm. Same here.

1186
01:01:49.506 --> 01:01:50.975
God... after all that.

1187
01:01:51.809 --> 01:01:53.142
Yeah.

1188
01:01:53.143 --> 01:01:55.512
George only outlived Carlyle
Burke by three weeks.

1189
01:01:59.884 --> 01:02:01.285
How you been?

1190
01:02:03.487 --> 01:02:05.322
I've been fine. thanks. You?

1191
01:02:07.457 --> 01:02:10.460
Uh. I don't suppose
you'd want a... a kitten.

1192
01:02:11.996 --> 01:02:13.329
Felix came back.

1193
01:02:13.330 --> 01:02:15.231
He got himself pregnant?

1194
01:02:15.232 --> 01:02:16.500
Yeah. Go figure.

1195
01:02:17.234 --> 01:02:18.334
How many?

1196
01:02:18.335 --> 01:02:19.335
Six.

1197
01:02:22.840 --> 01:02:24.241
He told me what you did.

1198
01:02:25.009 --> 01:02:26.476
Those letters.

1199
01:02:29.046 --> 01:02:30.480
That was very kind.

1200
01:02:31.982 --> 01:02:34.274
I might have done the same
if I'd been in your position.

1201
01:02:38.588 --> 01:02:40.490
I might have handled
things differently.

1202
01:02:45.529 --> 01:02:47.832
So. what'd he say to
you in his letter?

1203
01:02:50.267 --> 01:02:54.438
Uh... he told me not to
screw it up with you.

1204
01:02:56.240 --> 01:02:57.241
Hm.

1205
01:03:02.046 --> 01:03:03.046
Anyway...

1206
01:03:07.017 --> 01:03:09.786
Karl. I'd have to see
the kittens first.

1207
01:03:11.188 --> 01:03:12.222
I'll check with Felix.

1208
01:03:13.423 --> 01:03:14.859
See when it's convenient.

1209
01:03:16.026 --> 01:03:17.026
Okay.

1210
01:03:18.628 --> 01:03:20.264
Well you know
where to find me.

1211
01:03:21.465 --> 01:03:23.699
♪ Good night. good night

1212
01:03:23.700 --> 01:03:29.206
♪ Good night.

1213
01:03:32.376 --> 01:03:36.612
♪ Two lifelines

1214
01:03:36.613 --> 01:03:39.816
♪ On my hand

1215
01:03:43.487 --> 01:04:10.514
♪
